  "text": "The SpiderMonkey JavaScript source code parsing and compilation to bytecode chain consists of five main stages:\n\n## 1. Compilation Entry Points (js/src/frontend/BytecodeCompiler.h)\n\nThe main entry points are extern functions that initiate compilation:\n- `CompileGlobalScript()` - Compiles global scope JavaScript\n- `CompileEvalScript()` - Compiles eval() scripts\n- `CompileModule()` - Compiles ES6 modules\n- `CompileGlobalScriptToStencil()` - Creates a Stencil without instantiation\n- `CompileStandaloneFunction()` - Compiles function expressions\n\n## 2. Parser (js/src/frontend/Parser.h and Parser.cpp)\n\nThe Parser generates an Abstract Syntax Tree (AST) from JavaScript source text. Key components:\n\n- **Parser class hierarchy**: `Parser<ParseHandler, Unit>` is templated on:\n  - `ParseHandler`: Controls full parsing vs syntax-only parsing (FullParseHandler vs SyntaxParseHandler)\n  - `Unit`: Character type (char16_t or mozilla::Utf8Unit)\n\n- **Main parsing entry methods** (in Parser.cpp, lines 1776-1900+):\n  - `globalBody(GlobalSharedContext*)` - Parses global scope code\n  - `evalBody(EvalSharedContext*)` - Parses eval code \n  - `moduleBody(ModuleSharedContext*)` - Parses module code\n  - These methods parse the token stream and return ParseNode tree results\n\n- **Parser also contains**:\n  - TokenStream for lexical analysis\n  - ParseContext for scope tracking\n  - SharedContext for compilation state\n\n## 3. AST Node Types (js/src/frontend/ParseNode.h)\n\nParseNode.h defines all AST node types using a macro-based system:\n\n- Base node types: NullaryNode, UnaryNode, BinaryNode, TernaryNode, ListNode\n- Specialized nodes via `FOR_EACH_PARSE_NODE_KIND(F)` macro (lines 63-150+):\n  - FunctionNode - Function declarations/expressions\n  - ModuleNode - Module bodies\n  - CallNode - Function calls\n  - PropertyAccess/PropertyByValue - Property access\n  - ConditionalExpression - Ternary operators\n  - And many more statement and expression nodes\n\